<p>Hindu literature can be divided into two categories: <i><a href="Shruti" title="Shruti" class="mw-redirect">Shruti</a></i>–that which is revealed and <i><a href="Smriti" title="Smriti">Smriti</a></i>–that which is remembered. The Vedas constituting the former category are considered sacred <a href="Scripture" title="Scripture" class="mw-redirect">scripture</a>. Later texts like the various <a href="Shastra" title="Shastra">shastras</a> and the itihaasas form Smruti. Holding an ambiguous position between the Upanishads of the Vedas and the epics, the <a href="Bhagavad_Gita" title="Bhagavad Gita">Bhagavad Gita</a> is considered to be revered scripture by most Hindus today. All Shruti scriptures are composed in <a href="Sanskrit" title="Sanskrit">Sanskrit</a>. Much of the <a href="Morphology_(linguistics)" title="Morphology (linguistics)">morphology</a> inherent in the learning of Sanskrit is inextricably linked to study of the <a href="Vedas" title="Vedas">Vedas</a> and other early texts.<sup class="Template-Fact" style="white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href="Wikipedia_Citation_needed" title="Wikipedia:Citation needed"><span title="This claim needs references to reliable sources from September 2012">citation needed</span></a></i>]</sup></p>
<table id="toc" class="toc">
<tr>
